{"Caption": "Figure 2: Results from using Bag-of-words as TFIDF Features", "CaptionBB": [449, 275, 767, 289], "Mention": ["The most common type of feature used for topic and e-\nmail spam classification tasks is the bag-of-words, in which\nwords occurring on page are treated as features. To verify\nits utility, we created bag-of-words for the samples based on\ntheir textual content. We did not use stop lists or perform\nstemming. Results from using the binary feature encoding\nis depicted in Figure 1 and TFIDF encoding in Figure 2.\nClearly, bag-of-words is quite effective using binary fea-\ntures and a linear kernel. To analyze the discriminating fea-\ntures we used a simple approach of ordering features by\nweights assigned to them in the SVM model. It turns out\nthat the model was built around features which the human\neye would have typically overlooked. Blogs often contain\ncontent that expresses personal opinions, so words like \u201cI\u201d,\n\u201cWe\u201d, \u201cmy\u201d, \u201cwhat\u201d appear commonly on authentic blog\nposts. To this effect, the bag-of-words model is built on an\ninteresting \u201cblog content genre\u201d as a whole. In general, such\na content genre is not seen on theWeb, which partly explains\nwhy spam detection using local textual content is not all that\neffective there.\nIn all of the evaluations that follow binary features were\nthe most effective. In addition, polynomial kernels did not\nperform all that well in our domain of interest for binary\n"], "ImageBB": [483, 86, 738, 250], "ImageText": [{"TextLabelConf": 2, "Text": "1", "TextBB": [35, 3, 41, 13], "TextLabel": "yaxisvalue", "TextLabelGold": "yaxisvalue", "Rotation": 0}, {"TextLabelConf": 2, "Text": "0.9", "TextBB": [25, 43, 41, 53], "TextLabel": "yaxisvalue", "TextLabelGold": "yaxisvalue", "Rotation": 0}, {"TextLabelConf": 2, "Text": "0.8", "TextBB": [25, 83, 41, 93], "TextLabel": "yaxisvalue", "TextLabelGold": "yaxisvalue", "Rotation": 0}, {"TextLabelConf": 3, "Text": "A